    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-06-13T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-06-13T17:00:00-05:00" n="281"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d281">
                <head>281. Memorandum for the Record<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d281fn1"
                        >Source: <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> Library, National
                        Security File, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Special Committee Files,
                        Special Committee Meetings. Secret. See also <ref target="#d280">Document
                            280</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-06-13T18:00:00-04:00">June 13, 1967, 6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Minutes of Informal Meeting, 6:00 p.m., 13 June, Mr. <persName
                            corresp="#p_KNB1">Katzenbach</persName>’s office</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The group discussed whether the President should speak to the coming
                            <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> General Assembly and agreed on the
                        following preparatory actions: <list>
                            <label>a.</label>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KNB1">Katzenbach</persName> to cable
                                Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> laying out the
                                considerations so the Secretary could mull them over and be prepared
                                to discuss them at the 14 June Special Committee meeting.</item>
                            <label>b.</label>
                            <item>Messrs. <persName corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName> and <persName
                                    corresp="#p_REV1">E.V. Rostow</persName> to prepare separate
                                drafts of a <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> speech in time for the
                                President’s Wednesday night reading.</item>
                            <label>c.</label>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BLD1">Battle</persName> to assume
                                responsibility for producing a paper covering the whole range of
                                political and territorial problems to settle issues and making some
                                judgment on their acceptability. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BMG1"
                                    >Bundy</persName> to have a couple of non-government experts
                                produce independent papers along the same lines. Although these
                                papers must necessarily be tentative at this stage, they are
                                necessary as yardsticks for judging the content of the <gloss
                                    target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> speech.</item>
                            <label>d.</label>
                            <item>Messrs. <persName corresp="#p_BLD1">Battle</persName> and
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName> to call a joint
                                meeting of the <gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss> and IO
                                consultants for 15 June.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The group requested two studies: <list>
                            <label>a.</label>
                            <item>An <gloss target="#t_SNIE1">SNIE</gloss> on <persName
                                    corresp="#p_NGA1">Nasser</persName>’s prospects for survival,
                                including both economic and political vulnerabilities.</item>
                            <label>b.</label>
                            <item>A paper answering the questions: How long can Israel hold the
                                territory it has won? What are the costs?</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>The group noted the importance of getting a better picture of the nuclear
                        problem and tentatively agreed to ask Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KFD1"
                            >Kohler</persName> to take a look at this.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>McG B</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
